'''Deriba''' is a [[Pleistocene]] or [[Holocene]] [[caldera]] in [[Darfur]], [[Sudan]]. Part of the volcanoes of the [[Marrah Mountains|Marra Mountains]], it lies on the [[Darfur Dome|Darfur dome]] and like the [[Tagabo Hills]] and [[Meidob volcanic field|Meidob Hills]] volcanism may be the consequence of a [[mantle plume]]. The highest point of Sudan (after the separation of [[South Sudan]]) lies on the margin of the caldera.

The caldera lies atop a [[shield volcano]] or ash cone in the southern Marra Mountains, which developed first as a pile of [[Basalt|basaltic]] [[lava flows]] and later as layers of [[volcanic ash]] and [[tuff]], including the eruptions that formed the caldera. A large eruption occurred about 3,520 ± 100 years [[before present]], and [[Hot spring|hot springs]] and [[Fumarole|fumaroles]] are active to the present day.

Deriba contains two lakes, one in the northeastern side of the main caldera and the other in a cone in the southwestern sector of the Deriba caldera. The fresher southwestern lake is smaller but considerably deeper than the saltier northeastern lake; in the late Pleistocene the caldera was filled with a larger lake.

== Geography and geomorphology ==
[[File:Deriba map.jpg|thumb|Map of the Deriba caldera]]
Deriba lies in the [[Marra Mountains]] of [[Sudan]],{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=493}} Africa's geographic centre;<ref name="IssawiSallam2017" /> Deriba is in the southern sector of these mountains and close to the main summit thereof.{{sfn|Gillan|1918|p=263}}  The caldera rim became Sudan's new highest point, after the independence of [[South Sudan]].<ref name="Forbes" /> The town of [[Nyala, Sudan|Nyala]] lies south of Deriba.{{sfn|Vail|1972|p=251}} 

Deriba is an oval, {{convert|3|x|4|mi|km|order=flip}}{{sfn|Gillan|1918|p=265}} wide and {{convert|500|-|1000|m}} deep [[caldera]], with a [[volcanic cone]] occupying the southwestern part of the caldera floor. The rim of the caldera reaches a maximum elevation of {{convert|3024|m}} in the southwest.{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=493}} The caldera is cut into [[volcanic ash]], [[lapilli]], [[lava]]s, [[obsidian]] and [[tuff]]s, and the floor is strewn with [[pumice]] blocks.{{sfn|Lynes|Lynes|1921|p=123}}{{sfn|Vail|1972|p=259}} A gap lies in the eastern caldera wall.{{sfn|Williams|Morton|Parry|Adamson|1980|p=323}}

=== Lakes ===

Deriba contains two lakes, which are known as the "Deriba lakes". A {{convert|11.5|m}} deep lake occupies the northeastern area of the caldera,{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=493}} and being located in the lowest part of the caldera floor{{sfn|Hammerton|1968|p=136}} it is the [[sink]] of Deriba.{{sfn|Lynes|Lynes|1921|p=123}} In 1918 it had dimensions of {{convert|1350|x|1950|yd|m|order=flip}}, but by 1964 the size of the lake had increased.{{sfn|Hammerton|1968|p=138}} The lake is surrounded by a gradually sloping muddy beach with the exception of the northern shore.{{sfn|Hobbs|1918|p=360}} This lake is also known as the "female" lake, with green salty water.{{sfn|Gillan|1918|p=265}} The salt consists of [[chloride]], [[potassium]] and [[sodium]] salts.<ref name="FottKarim1973" />

The volcanic cone has a lake as well, which is {{convert|108|m}} deep{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=493}} and smaller, with a roughly rectangular shape that extends in north-south direction.{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=494}} In comparison to the other lake {{convert|0.75|mi|km|order=flip}} northwest, this "male" lake had dimensions of {{convert|900|x|1550|yd|m|order=flip}} in 1918. Steep slopes surround this lake,{{sfn|Gillan|1918|p=265}} which is filled with [[freshwater|fresh]]er water.{{sfn|Lynes|Lynes|1921|p=123}} Reportedly, the local [[Fur]] people considered the lake [[haunted house|haunted]],{{sfn|Hobbs|1918|p=361}} but the lakes were also used as a source for [[salt]].{{sfn|Hammerton|1968|p=141}}

Water levels in these lakes are fairly stable{{sfn|Lynes|Lynes|1921|p=124}} from season to season{{sfn|Hammerton|1968|p=139}} although evidence for substantial fluctuations have been found.{{sfn|Hammerton|1968|p=138}}{{sfn|Williams|Morton|Parry|Adamson|1980|p=305}} Together with several perennial [[stream]]s they are thus perennial waterbodies.{{sfn|Vail|1972|p=252}} Around the Deriba caldera, [[drainage]] occurs either southward or westward,{{sfn|Vail|1972|p=256}} leading into the [[Bahr al-Arab|Bahr El-Arab]] of the [[White Nile]] and the [[Chari River]] of [[Lake Chad]] respectively.<ref name="IssawiSallam2017" /> The lakes themselves have no surface outlets.{{sfn|Hobbs|1918|p=362}}

In the past, larger lakes existed inside the Deriba caldera. The first such lake stage has been dated to 19,000 years [[before present]] when water levels rose {{convert|25|m}} above the present-day levels, the second 19,600 - 16,000 years before present when they were {{convert|8|-|5|m}} higher than currently and the third 14,000 years before present, then {{convert|9|m}} above present-day. Similar lake stages have been documented in [[Trou au Natron]] in Tibesti, where shifts of the position of the [[Subtropical jet stream]] and the [[tropical depression]]s associated with the jet stream have been invoked as an explanation.<ref name="Maley2000" /><ref name="Soulié-Märsche2010" /> These lake stages have left [[limestone]] deposits in the caldera,{{sfn|Williams|Morton|Parry|Adamson|1980|p=305}} and it's likely that the lakes sometimes overflowed through the eastern caldera rim gap.{{sfn|Williams|Morton|Parry|Adamson|1980|p=325}}

== Geology ==

Deriba is part of [[Jebel Marra]] volcano, which together with the [[Tagabo Hills]] and the [[Meidob Hills]] is one of three [[volcanic field]]s in [[Darfur]];{{sfn|Wickens|1975|p=110}} these form the little known Darfur Volcanic Province.{{sfn|Franz|Pudlo|Urlacher|Haussmann|1994|p=614}} The Jebel Marra volcano is maximally {{convert|80|km}} wide and {{convert|200|km}} long in north-south direction, where the northern segment is centered around Jebel Gurgei.{{sfn|Vail|1972|p=251}} 

Jebel Marra consists of a pile of mostly [[basalt]]ic lava which has been covered by [[pumice]] and [[volcanic ash]] as well as [[pyroclastic]] rocks and [[ignimbrite]]s.<ref name="Francis1973" /> The Deriba caldera which forms the top of the entire complex,{{sfn|Wickens|1975|p=112}} which around Deriba has the appearance of a large ash cone{{sfn|Vail|1972|p=258}} or [[shield volcano]].{{sfn|Franz|Pudlo|Urlacher|Haussmann|1994|p=618}} Other, less spectacular [[Volcano|vents]] are found elsewhere in the Marra Mountains. Erosion has cut [[canyon]]s into the volcanic complex.{{sfn|Vail|1972|p=253}} The occurrence of volcanism has been explained with a [[mantle plume]] centered between Meidob and Jebel Marra.{{sfn|Franz|Pudlo|Urlacher|Haussmann|1994|p=621}}

The basement is formed by crystalline rocks, mainly [[metamorphosed]] [[gneiss]]es and [[schist]]s,{{sfn|Vail|1972|p=257}} and is a [[mobile belt]] of [[Pan-African orogeny|Panafrican]] age.{{sfn|Franz|Pudlo|Urlacher|Haussmann|1994|p=614}} They are in part covered by the [[Nubian Sandstone]]s of [[Cretaceous]] age and [[aeolian processes|aeolian]] sands,{{sfn|Wickens|1975|p=111}} and by the Jebel Marra massif which occupies a surface of {{convert|13000|km2}}.{{sfn|Wickens|1975|p=112}} Tectonic [[Geologic uplift|uplift]] of the [[Darfur Dome|Darfur dome]] commenced in the [[Cretaceous]]<ref name="DavidsonWilson1989" /> and resulted in a noticeable upwarp of the basement beneath Jebel Marra.<ref name="Francis1973" /> Two major tectonic [[lineament]]s intersect at Jebel Marra.{{sfn|Wickens|1975|p=111}}

=== Eruptive history ===

Volcanism in the southwestern Marra mountains took place between 4.35 million years ago and 60,000 years ago,{{sfn|Franz|Pudlo|Urlacher|Haussmann|1994|p=618}} subdivided into an Old Series and a New Series which is younger than 2 million years ago. The Deriba caldera probably formed either 60,000<ref name="DavidsonWilson1989" /> or 3,520 ± 100 years [[before present]] (BP), but activity continued with the volcanic cone inside of the caldera and peripheral vents, possibly into historical time.{{sfn|Wickens|1975|p=112}}

The 3,520 ± 100 BP eruption was a [[Plinian eruption]] that deposited [[pyroclastic]] material containing blocks of basement material. The ash fall from the eruption reaches thicknesses of {{convert|20|m}} as far as {{convert|5|km}} away from Deriba,<ref name="Francis1973" /> while [[pyroclastic flow]]s have been identified as far as {{convert|30|km}} from the caldera. The eruption has an estimated [[volcanic explosivity index]] of 4<ref name="GVP" /> and may be associated with the volcanic cone inside the caldera.{{sfn|Williams|Morton|Parry|Adamson|1980|p=305}}

The volcano was formerly considered to be [[extinct]].<ref name="Nature1966" /> [[Hot spring]]s whose temperature reaches {{convert|65|-|85|C}} and which may be supplied by [[magmatic water]]<ref name="Nature1966" /> and [[fumarole]]s, both within the caldera around the volcanic cone and in the surrounding Marra Mountains,{{sfn|Wickens|1975|p=112}}{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=494}} indicate that Jebel Marra and the Deriba caldera are a [[dormant volcano]].{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=494}} Reportedly, the exhalations of the fumaroles can kill birds and insects,<ref name="Nature1966" /> and some fumarolic vents may have formed between 1964 and 1966,<ref name="USGS" /> implying that the fumarolic activity may reflect a recent change of volcanic activity.{{sfn|Hammerton|1968|p=143}}

== Climate ==

Precipitation on Jebel Marra is about {{convert|1200|mm/year|in/year}},{{sfn|Wickens|1975|p=109}} the mountain lies at the southern margin of the [[Sahara]]<ref name="Soulié-Märsche2010" /> and receives more precipitation than the surrounding region.{{sfn|Hammerton|1968|p=136}} Between 12,000 and 8,000 years before present, the climate was wetter as a consequence of a northward shift of climate zones.{{sfn|Wickens|1975|p=120}}

== Biology ==

Vegetation around Deriba consists of grassland with scarce trees such as the [[wild olive]].{{sfn|Lynes|Lynes|1921|p=126}} The plant life is classified as [[Afromontane]], it also includes species from [[temperate]] climates.{{sfn|Wickens|1975|p=109}} It is likely that past humid periods permitted the expansion of [[Mediterranean]] species into the Jebel Marra mountains.{{sfn|Wickens|1975|p=118}} Presently, Jebel Marra may be a suitable site for agriculture.{{sfn|Vail|1972|p=252}} [[Semidesert]] and [[desert]] landscapes dominate the region around the Marra Mountains.{{sfn|Hammerton|1968|p=136}}

Generally, the lakes are salty, [[oxygen]] poor and remote and thus contain little plant or animal life.{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=502}} Some vegetation grows around the smaller lake, as well as in other parts of the Deriba caldera where water is available.{{sfn|Lynes|Lynes|1921|p=124}}

[[Copepod]]s live in the smaller lake, while the larger one is populated by [[blue-green alga]]e and [[rotifer]]s.{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=494}} ''[[Spirulina (genus)|Spirulina]]'' occurs in the large lake,{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=497}} and ''[[Melosira]]'' and ''[[Nitzscia]]'' [[diatom]]s have been identified in the small lake.{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=498}} The copepod ''[[Eucyclops gibsoni]]'' has been encountered in the small lake. Among the rotifers are ''[[Brachionus dimidiatus]]'', ''[[Brachionus plicatilis]]'', ''[[Hexarthra jenkinae]]''{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=498}} and ''[[Lecane bulla]]'', some of which also occur in the smaller lake.{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=499}} ''[[Ephedra]]'' flies are widespread around the large lake, and other insects were collected on the small lake.{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=500}} Birds are uncommon, with [[greenshank]]s, [[little grebe]]s, [[sacred ibis]] and [[stilt]]s.{{sfn|Green|Moghraby|Ali|2009|p=501}}

