{{Infobox organization | name = Regional Plan Association | bgcolor = <!-- header background color --> | fgcolor = <!-- header text color --> | image = Regional Plan Association logo.png | image_border = | size = 250 | alt = <!-- alt text; see [[WP:ALT]] --> | caption = | map = Regional Plan Association 31 County Area.png | msize = <!-- map size, optional, default 200px --> | malt = A color coordinated map of the 31 counties from [[New York (state)|New York]], [[New Jersey]], and [[Connecticut]] that are under the purview of the Regional Plan Association | mcaption = 31-county area{{sfn |Danielson|Doig|1982| pp=35–37}} | abbreviation = RPA | motto = | formation = 1922 | type = Non-Profit | status = <!--(ad hoc, treaty, foundation, etc)--> | purpose = Regional planning | headquarters = [[Manhattan]], [[New York City|New York]], {{flag|New York}} | location = | region_served = [[New York metropolitan area]] USA | leader_title = President | leader_name = [[Thomas K Wright]] | main_organ = <!--(gral. assembly, board of directors, etc)--> | parent_organization = <!--(if one)--> | affiliations = <!--(if any)--> | num_staff = 30 | num_volunteers = | budget = | website = {{URL|rpa.org}} | remarks = }}
The '''Regional Plan Association''' of the United States is an independent, not-for-profit regional planning organization, founded in 1922, that focuses on recommendations to improve the quality of life and economic competitiveness of a 31-county [[New York (state)|New York]]–[[New Jersey]]–[[Connecticut]] region in the [[New York metropolitan area]].{{sfn |Danielson|Doig|1982| pp=35–37}} Headquartered in [[New York City]], it has offices in [[Princeton, New Jersey]], and [[Stamford, Connecticut]].<ref name="Contact - Regional Plan Association">{{cite web|title=Contact - Regional Plan Association|url=http://www.rpa.org/about/contact-us|publisher=Regional Plan Association|accessdate=7 October 2014}}</ref>
== Regional plans ==
RPA has produced four strategic regional plans for the New York metropolitan region since the 1920s. The chronology of their plans is as follows: # The First Plan in 1929, developed under the leadership of [[Thomas Adams (architect)|Thomas Adams]], provided a guide for the area's road and transportation network.{{sfn |Fishman|2000| pp=65–88}} # The Second Plan, published as a series of reports in the 1960s, aimed at restructuring mass transit and reinvigorating deteriorating urban centers. # The Third Plan in 1996, "A Region at Risk," recommended improving regional mass transit, increasing protection of open space and maintaining employment in traditional urban centers. # The Fourth Plan in 2017 suggested improving the area's transportation network, making more affordable housing, implementing measures to fight climate change, and restructure the area's public institutions.<ref name="Fourth Regional Plan - Regional Plan Association">{{cite web|title=Fourth Regional Plan - Regional Plan Association|url=http://fourthplan.org/|publisher=Regional Plan Association|accessdate=30 November 2017}}</ref>
== Planning philosophy ==
The RPA program represents a philosophy of planning described by historian Robert Fishman as "metropolitanism," associated with the [[Chicago School of Sociology]]. It promotes large scale, industrial centers and the concentration of population rather than decentralized development. Its critics point out that this results in windfall real estate profits for downtown interests. Whether this approach to regional planning is efficient, particularly because of the infrastructure and energy required to sustain such concentration, has been questioned by scholars including James Howard Kunstler.{{sfn |Fishman|2000| pp=65–88}}
== Impact in the Tri-state area == Regional Plan Association's strategic plans have proposed numerous ideas and investments for the New York metropolitan area that have turned into major public works, economic development and open space projects, including: * The location of the [[George Washington Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news|title=For Hudson Bridge Above 125th Street|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F03E2D81439E033A2575BC2A9649D946295D6CF|accessdate=7 October 2014|publisher=The New York Times|date=December 28, 1923}}</ref> * The preservation of the [[The Palisades (Hudson River)|Palisades]] and the construction of the [[Palisades Interstate Parkway]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Binnewies|first1=Robert O.|title=Palisades: 100,000 Acres in 100 Years|date=2001|publisher=Fordham University Press|page=203|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XHMtDurA9EAC&pg=PA203&lpg=PA203&dq=%22It+has+also+been+my+hope+that+a+strip+of+this+land+of+adequate+width+might+ultimately+be+developed+as+a+parkway,+along+the+general+lines%22&source=bl&ots=KzpYishnGt&sig=j1hyt3k481vOnM4FF1gHfxtYTaw&hl=en&sa=X&ei=fEg0VNqjIJXesATw8IKgDw&ved=0CCEQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=%22It%20has%20also%20been%20my%20hope%20that%20a%20strip%20of%20this%20land%20of%20adequate%20width%20might%20ultimately%20be%20developed%20as%20a%20parkway%2C%20along%20the%20general%20lines%22&f=false|accessdate=7 October 2014}}</ref> * The redevelopment of [[Governors Island]], through the RPA-led coalition Governors Island Alliance.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Governors Island Alliance|title=Our Mission|url=http://www.governorsislandalliance.org/}}</ref> * The establishment of urban national parks like the [[Gateway National Recreation Area]] in [[Jamaica Bay]]. * The revitalization of the regional centers like [[Downtown Brooklyn]], [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], and [[Stamford, Connecticut|Stamford]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Regional Plan Association|title=Shaping the Region|url=http://www.rpa.org/regional-plans#shaping-the-region|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref>
